    <item>
      <title>Vermouth</title>
      <link>https://sidecar.keithjgrant.com/ingredients/vermouth/</link>
      <pubDate>Mon, 08 Jan 2018 13:09:24 -0500</pubDate>
      
      <guid>https://sidecar.keithjgrant.com/ingredients/vermouth/</guid>
      <description>

&lt;h2 id=&#34;types&#34;&gt;Types&lt;/h2&gt;

&lt;p&gt;There are several types of vermouth, the most common being ”dry” and “sweet”. Dry vermouth is known for its use in a &lt;a href=&#34;https://sidecar.keithjgrant.com/drinks/martini&#34;&gt;martini&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;h2 id=&#34;brands&#34;&gt;Brands&lt;/h2&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The &lt;em&gt;Martini &amp;amp; Rossi&lt;/em&gt; brand is the most readily available in the United States. Their dry vermouth is passable. But I find their sweet (called “Rosso”) to be medicinal and a quick way to ruin a drink.&lt;/p&gt;
</description>
